{"title_page": "Jean Sandberg", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Underlinked|date=April 2020}}\n{{Orphan|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n\n[[Image:Jean Sandberg.jpg|thumb|220px|Jean Sandberg in 1884]]\n\n'''Jean Sandberg''', (4 August 1852 in [[Stockholm]] - 5 December 1917) was a Swedish actor.<ref>[http://arkivet.dn.se/arkivet/tidning/1889-12-13/7594/2 Arkivet Jean sandberg] Retrieved 29 June 2017{{Dead link|date=October 2017}}</ref> He worked at Stora teatern we he stayed for about ten years. He had roles in plays like F\u00f6reningsfesten, Visitl\u00e5dan, Sk\u00f6na Helena and Nya garnisonen. During the 1890s he worked at Albert Ranfts theaters until he in May 1897 left his acting career.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tidningar.kb.se/8224221/1896-05-11/edition/0/part/1/page/3/?q=%22Med+Sveriges+allmoge%22+arenateatern&sort=asc|title=S\u00f6k bland svenska dagstidningar|website=tidningar.kb.se|accessdate=29 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171029013803/http://tidningar.kb.se/8224221/1896-05-11/edition/0/part/1/page/3/?q=%22Med+Sveriges+allmoge%22+arenateatern&sort=asc|archive-date=29 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHe also was productive in arts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://auctionet.com/sv/287236-jean-sandberg-marinmotiv-olja-pa-duk-signerad-och-daterad-86|title=JEAN SANDBERG. Marinmotiv, olja p\u00e5 duk, signerad och daterad 86. Konst - M\u00e5leri \u2013 Auctionet|website=auctionet.com|accessdate=29 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons category-inline|Jean Sandberg}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sandberg, Jean}}\n[[Category:1852 births]]\n[[Category:1917 deaths]]\n[[Category:Swedish actors]]\n[[Category:19th-century Swedish male actors]]\n[[Category:Swedish male stage actors]]\n\n\n{{Sweden-actor-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[Image:Jean Sandberg.jpg|thumb|220px|Jean Sandberg in 1884]] \n\n'''Jean Sandberg''', (4 August 1852 in [[Stockholm]] - 5 December 1917) was a Swedish actor.<ref>[http://arkivet.dn.se/arkivet/tidning/1889-12-13/7594/2 Arkivet Jean sandberg] Retrieved 29 June 2017{{Dead link|date=October 2017}}</ref> He worked at Stora teatern we he stayed for about ten years. He had roles in plays like F\u00f6reningsfesten, Visitl\u00e5dan, Sk\u00f6na Helena and Nya garnisonen. During the 1890s he worked at Albert Ranfts theaters until he in May 1897 left his acting career. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://tidningar.kb.se/8224221/1896-05-11/edition/0/part/1/page/3/?q=%22Med+Sveriges+allmoge%22+arenateatern&sort=asc|title=S\u00f6k bland svenska dagstidningar|website=tidningar.kb.se|accessdate=29 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171029013803/http://tidningar.kb.se/8224221/1896-05-11/edition/0/part/1/page/3/?q=%22Med+Sveriges+allmoge%22+arenateatern&sort=asc|archive-date=29 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHe also was productive in arts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://auctionet.com/sv/287236-jean-sandberg-marinmotiv-olja-pa-duk-signerad-och-daterad-86|title=JEAN SANDBERG. Marinmotiv, olja p\u00e5 duk, signerad och daterad 86. Konst - M\u00e5leri \u2013 Auctionet|website=auctionet.com|accessdate=29 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons category inline|Jean Sandberg}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sandberg, Jean}}\n\n[[Category:1852 births]]\n[[Category:1917 deaths]]\n[[Category:Swedish actors]]\n[[Category:19th-century Swedish male actors]]\n[[Category:Swedish male stage actors]]\n\n{{Sweden-actor-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control, addedorphan,underlinkedtags", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jean_Sandberg"}
{"title_page": "Eight Crazy Nights", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2014}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Eight Crazy Nights\n| image = 8crazynights.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = Theatrical release poster\n| director = Seth Kearsley\n| producer = {{plainlist|\n* [[Adam Sandler]]\n* [[Allen Covert]]\n* [[Jack Giarraputo]]\n}}\n| writer = {{plainlist|\n* Adam Sandler\n* Allen Covert\n* Brooks Arthur\n* Brad Isaacs\n}}\n| story = Adam Sandler\n| starring = {{plainlist|\n* Adam Sandler\n* [[Jackie Sandler|Jackie Titone]]\n* Austin Stout\n* [[Rob Schneider]]\n}}\n| music = {{plainlist|\n* [[Teddy Castellucci]]\n* Marc Ellis\n* [[Ray Ellis]]\n}}\n| narrator = Rob Schneider\n| editing = Amy Budden\n| studio = {{plainlist|\n* [[Columbia Pictures]]<ref name=afi>{{cite web|url=https://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/moviedetails/62143?sid=9f9f2e79-a091-4a55-bc79-2ddee0de3961&sr=3.55131&cp=1&pos=0|title=Adam Sandler's Eight Crazy Nights  (2002)|work=[[AFI Catalog of Feature Films]]|accessdate=November 11, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171112021849/https://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/moviedetails/62143?sid=9f9f2e79-a091-4a55-bc79-2ddee0de3961&sr=3.55131&cp=1&pos=0|archive-date=November 12, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[Happy Madison Productions]]<ref name=\"allmovie\">{{cite web|title=Adam Sandler's Eight Crazy Nights|url=https://www.allmovie.com/movie/adam-sandlers-eight-crazy-nights-v267568|website=[[AllMovie]]|accessdate=February 24, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170724032239/http://www.allmovie.com/movie/adam-sandlers-eight-crazy-nights-v267568|archive-date=July 24, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n}}\n| distributor = [[Sony Pictures Motion Picture Group#Sony Pictures Releasing|Sony Pictures Releasing]]<ref name=\"afi\" /> \n| released = {{Film date|2002|11|27}}\n| runtime = 76 minutes\n| country = United States\n| language = English\n| budget = $34 million<ref>{{cite\nweb|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt027163/\n|website=[[IMDb]]|accessdate=November 18, 2018}}</ref>\n| gross = $23.8 million\n}}\n'''''Eight Crazy Nights''''' (also known as '''''Adam Sandler's Eight Crazy Nights''''') is a 2002 American [[Adult animation|adult]] [[traditional animation|animated]] [[musical film|musical]] [[comedy-drama film|comedy-drama]] [[Christmas film|Christmas]] and [[Hanukkah film]] directed by Seth Kearsley and produced, co-written by, and starring [[Adam Sandler]] in his first voice-acting role. The film is animated in the style of television holiday specials and, unlike most mainstream holiday films, centers on Jewish characters during the [[Hanukkah]] season, as opposed to the Christian celebration of [[Christmas]]. \n\nThis is also [[Happy Madison Productions]]' first animated film. The film's title is taken from a line in Sandler's series of songs called ''[[The Chanukah Song]]'' that compares the gift-giving traditions of [[Christmas]] and [[Hanukkah|Chanukah]]: ''\"Instead of one day of presents, we get eight crazy nights!\"'' A new version of ''The Chanukah Song'' also plays over the film's closing credits. It has been called the best known [[Hanukkah film]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Jews deserve a better Hanukkah movie than Adam Sandler's \"Eight Crazy Nights\" |url=https://www.salon.com/2018/12/01/jews-deserve-a-better-hanukkah-movie-than-adam-sandlers-eight-crazy-nights/amp |accessdate=7 December 2019 |agency=Salon}}</ref>\n\nThe film has received a cult following, especially among those in the [[Jewish community]], as it is one of the highest-profile and most-known Hanukkah films.<ref>{{cite news |title=Jews deserve a better Hanukkah movie than Adam Sandler's \"Eight Crazy Nights\" |url=https://www.salon.com/2018/12/01/jews-deserve-a-better-hanukkah-movie-than-adam-sandlers-eight-crazy-nights/amp |accessdate=7 December 2019 |agency=Salon}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nIn December 2001 in the small fictional town of Dukesberry, [[New Hampshire]], Davey Stone is a 33-year-old [[Jews|Jewish]] [[Alcoholism|alcoholic]] troublemaker with a long [[criminal record]], whose antics have long earned him the community's animosity. Davey is arrested for [[dine and dash|refusing to pay his bill]] at Mr. Chang's Chinese restaurant, attempting to evade arrest (\"Davey's Song\"), stealing a [[snowmobile]], and destroying festive [[Ice sculpture|ice sculptures]] in the process. At Davey's trial, Whitey Duvall, a 70-year-old volunteer referee from Davey's former basketball league, intervenes. At Whitey's suggestion, the judge sentences Davey to [[community service]] as a referee-in-training for Whitey's Youth Basketball League. Under the terms of the community service, if Davey commits a crime before his sentence is completed, he will serve 10 years in prison.\n\nThe next day, Davey's first game ends in disaster. After Davey causes disruptions and torments an obese player for his [[gynecomastia]], Whitey suffers a [[grand mal seizure]], and the game is abruptly halted.  Attempting to calm Davey down, Whitey takes him to the mall, where they meet Davey's childhood friend Jennifer Friedman and her son Benjamin. Whitey reminds Davey that he lost his chance with Jennifer 20 years earlier, but Davey secretly still has feelings for her.\n\nAs time progresses, Davey and Whitey's relationship becomes more strained. Whitey's various attempts to encourage Davey are met with humiliation and assault--including but not limited to Davey knocking Whitey into a [[chemical toilet|porta-potty]] then spraying him with a hose when he climbs out, causing him to be frozen in defecation for several hours before a group of grazing reindeer licks him out. When Davey gets home (\"Long Ago\") his trailer is being burned down by a man who lost a basketball match to him earlier and was forced to chew on a [[jock strap]]. Davey runs into the burning trailer to rescue a [[Hanukkah]] card from his late parents, then watches the trailer burn down. Whitey opens his home to Davey, who reluctantly accepts; also living there is Whitey's [[Diabetes|diabetic]] [[fraternal twin]] sister Eleanore. The Duvall household has many complex rules, to which Whitey refers as [[technical foul]]s (\"Technical Foul\"). Davey seemingly overcomes them and starts to turn his life around.\n\nBut Davey's progress in reforming stops short when Whitey recalls what happened two decades ago: En route to one of Davey's basketball games, his parents were killed in a car accident when a truck skidded on [[black ice]] and swerved into them, and Davey learned of their deaths when the police showed up at the end of his game to inform him. Devastated by the loss of his loving parents and leaping from foster home to foster home, Davey spent the next 20 years numbing his pain with alcohol and petty crime. Uncomfortable with this reminder of his tragic, painful childhood, Davey loses his temper and insults both Whitey and Eleanore and Whitey kicks Davey out, much to Davey's relief.\n\nDavey spends the rest of the day drinking, and that night he breaks into the closed mall. In his drunken stupor, he imagines the logos of various stores coming to life and confronting him about his inability to grieve for his parents, which they identify as the source of his alcoholism (\"Intervention Song\"). He finally opens his parents' Hanukkah card, which contains a heartfelt message praising him for being a good son, and two photos: one of a young Davey and Jennifer at one of their basketball games, and one with his late parents. Davey finally cries and comes to terms with his loss. Just then the police arrive to arrest him, but he escapes and boards a bus to [[New York City]]. En route, the bus is forced to stop when a single thumbtack in the road punctures all eight rear tires. Reminded of the Miracle of Hanukkah, Davey walks off the bus, intending to find Whitey and make amends with him.\n\nDavey finds Whitey at the All-Star Banquet, an annual town celebration in which one member of the community is recognized for positive contributions to Dukesberry with the \"Dukesberry All-Star Patch\" which Whitey has wanted for 35 years. When Whitey is passed over for seemingly the final time, he decides to move to [[Florida]] and live the rest of his life in [[anonymity]]. Risking arrest, Davey enters the hall and informs everyone of Whitey's many selfless contributions to Dukesberry throughout his life. The ashamed townspeople acknowledge the error of their decision (\"Bum Biddy\"). Davey leads them to Whitey, who has gone to the mall with Eleanore to \"speak to it\" one more time. The townspeople thank Whitey for his service over the years and the Mayor officially grants him the Patch Award. All 34 previous recipients of the awards give theirs to Whitey. Davey and Jennifer reconcile and Whitey goes into a seizure, which he calls \"the happiest seizure of my life!\"\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Adam Sandler]] as Davey Stone/Whitey Duvall/Eleanore Duvall\n* [[Jackie Sandler|Jackie Titone]]<!--This was prior to her marriage to Sandler.--> as Jennifer Friedman.\n** [[Alison Krauss]] as her singing voice\n* Austin Stout as Benjamin Friedman, Jennifer's excitable 11-year-old son.\n* [[Rob Schneider]] as The Narrator/Mr. York, a Chinese restaurant waiter.\n* [[Kevin Nealon]] as Mayor Dewey, the Mayor of Dukesberry.\n* [[Norm Crosby]] as the Judge.\n* [[Jon Lovitz]] as Tom Baltezor, a competitor in the All-Star Banquet for the patch and the initial winner of it. He notably had no left hand, having lost it in a childhood accident and having a hook in its place.\n\n;Store logos\n* [[Dylan and Cole Sprouse]] as [[KB Toys]] soldiers\n* [[Tyra Banks]] as [[Victoria's Secret]] gown\n* [[Blake Clark]] as [[Radio Shack]] walkie-talkie\n* [[Peter Dante]] as [[Foot Locker]] referee\n* [[Ellen Albertini Dow]] as [[See's Candies]] box\n* [[Kevin Farley]] as [[Panda Express]] panda\n* Lari Friedman as [[The Coffee Bean & Tea Leaf]] cup\n* [[Tom Kenny]] as [[The Sharper Image]] chair\n* [[Carl Weathers]] as [[General Nutrition Centers|GNC]] bottle\n\n==Production==\nThe film was animated by Anvil Studios, [[A. Film A/S]], [[Bardel Entertainment]], Goldenbell Animation, Marina Motion Animation, Spaff Animation, Tama Production, Time Lapse Pictures, [[Warner Bros. Animation]], [[Y. R. Studio]], and [[Yowza! Animation]]. It was the only animated film that [[Adam Sandler]] worked on until ''[[Hotel Transylvania]]'' in 2012, and remains the only traditionally-animated film to have his involvement.\n\nSeth Kearsley revealed in an email to Doug Walker ([[The Nostalgia Critic]]) that certain elements of the movie that were notorious, specifically the feces-eating deer scene and even Whitey's voice (which was originally more higher-pitched and annoying), were intended to be cut, but were kept due to \"focus groups\" who had seen the film (who lowered Whitey's voice down), as well as the fact that the product placements were used without permission.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=497iTevXQ8M|title=Nostalgia Critic Real Thoughts on 8 Crazy Nights|website=[[YouTube]]|publisher=Channel Awesome|date=April 10, 2015|accessdate=August 9, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190823215530/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=497iTevXQ8M&gl=US&hl=en&has_verified=1&bpctr=9999999999|archive-date=August 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n''Eight Crazy Nights'' came in at fifth place on its opening weekend among U.S. box office, making only $14 million since its Wednesday launch. It only grossed a total of $23.6 million in North America and negligible foreign box office receipts, for a total of only $23.8 million worldwide. This made ''Eight Crazy Nights'' become a [[Box-office bomb|box office bomb]], losing an approximate at lowest $10.5 million to up to $44.6 million.\n\n===Critical response===\nThe film received largely negative reviews. [[Rotten Tomatoes]] gives the film a rating of 12% and an average score of 3.1/10, based on 109 reviews, with the consensus saying \"Sandler returns to his roots in this nauseating concoction filled with [[potty humor]] and [[product placement]]s.\"<ref>{{rotten-tomatoes|adam_sandlers_eight_crazy_nights|Eight Crazy Nights}}</ref> Top film critic [[Roger Ebert]] gave the film two out of four possible stars and derided the movie's dour tone, saying that \"The holidays aren't very cheerful in Sandlerville.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/adam-sandlers-eight-crazy-nights-2002 |title=Eight Crazy Nights |last=Ebert |first=Roger |year=2002 |access-date=December 27, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161228031823/http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/adam-sandlers-eight-crazy-nights-2002 |archive-date=December 28, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> However, on his review program, co-host [[Richard Roeper]] gave the film a \"Thumbs Up!\" Sandler won a [[Kids' Choice Award]] for Best Voice in an Animated Movie in 2003 and was nominated for the [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Actor]], along with ''[[Mr. Deeds]]''.\n\n==Home media==\n''Eight Crazy Nights'' was released November 4, 2003 on [[Videocassette|VHS]] and single- and two-disc edition [[DVD]]. The two-disc \"special edition\" features [[deleted scene]]s, several [[Audio commentary|audio commentaries]], and Sandler's [[short film]] \"A Day with the Meatball\", among other special features.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0271263/dvd|title=Eight Crazy Nights (2002) - DVD details|access-date=June 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041012113919/http://imdb.com/title/tt0271263/dvd|archive-date=October 12, 2004|url-status=live}}</ref> A [[Blu-ray]] version of the film was released on December 13, 2016.\n\n==Awards==\n;Kids' Choice Awards, USA 2003\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Award \n! Category \n! Nominee\n! Result\n|-\n| Blimp Award\n| Favorite Voice from an Animated Movie \n| Adam Sandler \n| {{Won}}\n|}\n\n;Razzie Awards 2003\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Award \n! Category \n! Nominee\n! Result\n|-\n| [[Razzie Award]]\n| Worst Actor and Most Flatulent Teen-Targeted Movie \n| Adam Sandler For ''[[Mr. Deeds]]'' and ''Eight Crazy Nights''\n| {{Nominated}}\n|}\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Adam Sandler's Eight Crazy Nights Soundtrack\n| type       = soundtrack\n| artist     = [[Adam Sandler]] and Eight Crazy Nights Cast\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = November 27, 2002\n| recorded   = 2002\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = Soundtrack\n| length     = 26:34\n| label      = [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]/[[Sony Music]] Soundtrax\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\nThe soundtrack of the film was released on November 27, 2002 by Columbia/Sony Music Soundtrax.<ref>{{cite web | title =Amazon.com:  Adam Sandler's Eight Crazy Nights: Adam Sandler, Ray Ellis, Teddy Castellucci, Various Artists: Music | work =[[Amazon.com]] | date =November 19, 2002 | url =https://www.amazon.com/Adam-Sandlers-Eight-Crazy-Nights/dp/B0000787FX | accessdate =2012-07-17 | archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20170607232233/https://www.amazon.com/Adam-Sandlers-Eight-Crazy-Nights/dp/B0000787FX | archive-date =June 7, 2017 | url-status =live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title =Amazon.com:  Adam Sandler's Eight Crazy Nights: Various: MP3 Downloads | work =[[Amazon.com]] | date =November 19, 2002 | url =https://www.amazon.com/Eight-Crazy-Nights/dp/B0013AYVN8/ref=tmm_msc_title_0/192-2758806-0216028 | accessdate = 2012-07-17}}</ref> The soundtrack contains every song in the film, including the new installment of \"The Chanukah Song\" and a deleted song, called \"At the Mall\", sung by Whitey as he strolls through the mall in an alternate opening, which is included in the DVD release.\n\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column    = Artist\n| collapsed       = no\n| headline        =\n| title1          = Davey's Song\n| extra1          = [[Adam Sandler]]\n| length1         = 2:16\n| titl