us}}|ubl=true|[[The Hit Factory]] <br />{{small|([[New York City, New York]])}}|[[Criteria Studios]] <br />{{small|([[Miami, Florida]]}})|[[Marvin's Room (studio)|Marvin's Room]] <br />{{small|([[Los Angeles, California]])}}|[[Rodney Jerkins|Darkchild Studios]] <br />{{small|(Los Angeles, California)}}|[[Record Plant]] <br />{{small|(Los Angeles, California)}}|Future Recording Studio <br />{{small|([[Norfolk, Virginia]]}})|[[Sony Music Studios|Sony Studios]] <br />{{small|(New York City, New York}})|[[Ocean Way Recording|Record One]] <br />{{small|(Los Angeles, California)}}|[[DJ Jazzy Jeff|A Touch of Jazz Studios]] <br />{{small|([[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]])}}|Brandon's Way Recording <br />{{small|(Los Angeles, California)}}|[[Capitol Studios]] <br />{{small|([[Hollywood]], California)}}}}\n| genre        = <!--Sourced in \"Music and lyrics\" section. Do not add unsourced genres -->\n*[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n*[[Pop music|pop]]\n*[[Soul music|soul]]\n| length       = 76:48\n| label        = {{hlist|[[Epic Records|Epic]]|[[Sony Music Entertainment|  Sony]]}}\n| producer     = \n*Michael Jackson\n*[[Rodney Jerkins]]\n*[[Teddy Riley]]\n*[[Dr. Freeze]]\n*[[Dre & Vidal|Andre Harris]]\n*[[Babyface (musician)|Kenneth\" Babyface\" Edmonds]]\n*[[R. Kelly]]\n| prev_title   = [[20th Century Masters&nbsp;\u2013 The Millennium Collection: The Best of Michael Jackson]]\n| prev_year    = 2000\n| next_title   = [[Love Songs (Michael Jackson album)|Love Songs]]\n| next_year    = 2002\n| misc         = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[Michael Jackson]] studio album\n | type       = studio\n | prev_title = [[HIStory: Past, Present and Future, Book I]]\n | prev_year  = 1995\n | title      = Invincible\n | year       = 2001\n | next_title =\n | next_year  =\n}}\n{{Singles\n | name        = Invincible\n | type        = Studio album\n | single1     = [[You Rock My World]]\n | single1date = {{start date|mf=yes|2001|08|22}}\n | single2     = [[Cry (Michael Jackson song)|Cry]]\n | single2date = {{start date|mf=yes|2001|12|3}}\n | single3     = [[Butterflies (Michael Jackson song)|Butterflies]]\n | single3date = {{start date|mf=yes|2002|2|8}}\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Invincible''''' is the final [[studio album]] by American singer [[Michael Jackson]] released October 30, 2001, on [[Epic Records]]. It was Jackson's sixth studio album released through Epic, and his last released before [[Death of Michael Jackson|his death in 2009]]. An extensive and laborious album to make, Jackson started the multi genre production in 1997, and did not finish until eight weeks before the album's October 2001 release. It was reported that it cost thirty million dollars to make the album,<ref name=\"promotioninfo\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1455976/20020708/jackson_michael.jhtml |title=Michael Jackson Shocks Al Sharpton By Calling Tommy Mottola A Racist |author=Jennifer Vineyard |work=MTV |publisher=Viacom |date=2002-07-02 |accessdate=2010-02-13}}</ref> making it the most expensive album ever made.<ref name=\"Branigan 20m\">{{cite news|last=Branigan|first=Tania|title=Jackson spends \u00a320m to be Invincible|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2001/sep/08/taniabranigan|accessdate=2013-02-16|newspaper=The Guardian|date=September 8, 2001}}</ref> The album features appearances from [[Carlos Santana]] and [[The Notorious B.I.G.]]. ''Invincible'' incorporates [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]], [[Pop music|pop]] and [[Soul music|soul]]. Similarly to Jackson's previous material, the album explores themes such as [[love]], [[Romance (love)|romance]], [[Isolation (health care)|isolation]], [[media criticism]], and [[Social issue|social issues]]. \n\nUnlike with Jackson's post-''[[Thriller (album)|Thriller]]'' studio albums, there was no world tour to promote ''Invincible''; a tour was planned, but canceled due to conflicts between Jackson and [[Sony Music Entertainment]]. Following Sony's decision to abruptly end all promotion for the album, Jackson made allegations in July 2002 that [[Tommy Mottola]] was a \"devil\" and a \"racist\" who did not support his [[African Americans|African-American]] artists but used them for his own personal gain. \n\n''Invincible'' debuted at number one on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and in ten other countries worldwide. As well as \"You Rock My World\", the album spawned three more singles: \"[[Cry (Michael Jackson song)|Cry]]\", \"[[Butterflies (Michael Jackson song)|Butterflies]]\" and the [[promotional single]] \"[[Speechless (Michael Jackson song)|Speechless]]\". \"You Rock My World\" was the album's most successful single, peaking at number ten on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. It was Jackson's last top 10 hit before his death. Although ''Invincible'' was one of the best-selling albums of 2001, it received mixed reviews. However, in retrospective reviews the album has gained more positive reviews and has been credited as an early development of [[dubstep]].<ref name=\"Nanke\">{{Cite web|url=https://kennedytorch.org/14178/artsculture/review-jacksons-invincible-is-underappreciated/|title=Review: Jackson\u2019s Invincible is under-appreciated|last=Nanke|first=Ashton|website=Kennedy Torch|access-date=2019-12-15}}</ref><ref name=\"OToole\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=UNCGDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT451&lpg=PT451&dq=michael+jackson+invincible+dubstep&source=bl&ots=DThiYmyFJt&sig=ACfU3U3DTLclEQB4caVnnUtWUILxTm2jQQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiC6e-btrfmAhWWi1wKHTEoBw84ChDoATADegQICRAB|title=Michael Jackson FAQ: All That's Left to Know About the King of Pop|last=O'Toole|first=Kit|date=2015-10-01|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=978-1-4950-4599-8|language=en}}</ref>\n\nHaving sold approximately 6 million copies worldwide, and being certified [[RIAA certification|2\u00d7 Platinum]] in January 2002 by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA), sales for ''Invincible'' were notably low compared to Jackson's previous releases, due to the lack of promotion, no supporting world tour and his label dispute. ''Invincible'' received one [[Grammy Award]] nomination, with \"You Rock My World\" being nominated for [[Grammy Award for Best Male Pop Vocal Performance|Best Male Pop Vocal Performance]]. In 2009, ''Invincible'' was voted by readers of ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' as the Best Album of the Decade.\n\n==Background==\nJackson had been recording solo studio albums since ''[[Got to Be There]]'' for [[Motown]] in 1971. During his time as a member of [[the Jacksons]], he frequently wrote material for the group after they left Motown in 1975 and began working on more projects as a solo artist, which eventually led to recording his own solo albums for [[Epic Records]], notably ''[[Off the Wall]]'' (1979), ''[[Thriller (Michael Jackson album)|Thriller]]'' (1982), ''[[Bad (album)|Bad]]'' (1987), and [[Dangerous (Michael Jackson album)|''Dangerous'']] (1991). The success of ''Thriller'', which, as of 2020, still holds its place as the best selling album of all time with a reported 66 million units sold, often over-shadowed Jackson's other projects. Prior to the release of ''Invincible'', Jackson had not released any new material since ''[[Blood on the Dance Floor: HIStory in the Mix]]'' in 1997, or a studio album since ''[[HIStory]]'' in 1995. ''Invincible'' was thus looked at as Jackson's 'career come back'.<ref name=\"ALG Invincible\">{{allmusic|album|invincible-mw0000011263|author=[[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]]|accessdate=2010-02-12}}</ref>\n\n''Invincible'' was dedicated to the fifteen-year-old Afro-Norwegian boy [[Benjamin Hermansen|Benjamin \"Benny\" Hermansen]] who was stabbed to death by a group of [[neo-Nazi]]s in [[Oslo]], Norway, in January 2001.<ref name=\"dedication\"/> The reason for this tribute was partly due to the fact that another Oslo youth, Omer Bhatti, Jackson's friend, was also a good friend of Hermansen.<ref name=\"dedication\"/> The dedication in the album reads, \"Michael Jackson gives 'special thanks': ''This album is dedicated to Benjamin 'Benny' Hermansen. May we continue to remember not to judge a man by the color of his skin, but the content of his character. Benjamin ... we love you ... may you rest in peace.''\"<ref name=\"dedication\">{{cite web|url=http://www.aftenposten.no/english/local/article216474.ece |title=Jacko dedicates Invincible to Benjamin |author=Liz McNamaba |work=[[Aftenposten]] |publisher=[[Schibsted|Schibsted ASA]] |date=2001-10-23 |accessdate=2010-02-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090309155446/http://www.aftenposten.no/english/local/article216474.ece |archivedate=March 9, 2009 }}</ref> The album is also dedicated to Nicholette Sottile and his parents [[Joe Jackson (manager)|Joseph]] and [[Katherine Jackson]].<ref name=\"dedication\"/>\n\n==Production==\nJackson began recording new material for the album in October 1997, and finished with \"You Are My Life\" being recorded only eight weeks before the album's release in October 2001 \u2013 the most extensive recording of Jackson's career.<ref name=\"mtvinfo1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1435389/20001221/jackson_michael.jhtml |title=Michael Jackson Nearing Completion Of New LP |author=Brian Hiatt |work=[[MTV]] |publisher=[[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]] |date=2000-12-21 |accessdate=2011-04-03}}</ref> The tracks with Rodney Jerkins were recorded at the Hit Factory in Miami, Florida.<ref name=\"vibe\">{{cite web |url=http://www.vibe.com/mt/2009/09/rodney-jerkins-talks-mjs-last-studio-album-invincible/ |title=Rodney Jerkin's Talks MJ's Last Studio Album, Invincible |author=Linda Hobbs |work=[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]] |publisher=[[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]] |date=2009-09-05 |accessdate=2010-02-13}}</ref> Jackson had shown interest in including a rapper on at least one song, and had noted that he did not want a 'known rapper'.<ref name=\"mtvinfo1\"/> Jackson's spokesperson suggested New Jersey rapper named Fats; after Jackson heard the finished product of the song, the two agreed to record another song together for the album.<ref name=\"mtvinfo1\"/> [[Rodney Jerkins]] stated that Jackson was looking to record material in a different musical direction than his previous work, describing the new direction as \"edgier\".<ref name=\"mtvinfo1\"/> Jackson received credit for both writing and producing a majority of the songs on ''Invincible''.  Aside from Jackson, the album features productions by Jerkins, [[Teddy Riley (producer)|Teddy Riley]], [[Andre Harris]], [[Andreao Heard|Andraeo \"Fanatic\" Heard]], [[Babyface (musician)|Kenneth \"Babyface\" Edmonds]], [[R. Kelly]] and [[Dr. Freeze]] Bill Gray and writing credits from Kelly, [[Fred Jerkins III]], [[LaShawn Daniels]], Nora Payne and Robert Smith.<ref name=\"linernotes\">''Invincible'' liner notes [[Epic Records]] (2001).</ref> The album is the third collaboration between Jackson and Riley, the other two being ''[[Dangerous (Michael Jackson album)|Dangerous]]'' and ''[[Blood on the Dance Floor: HIStory in the Mix]]''. ''Invincible'' is Jackson's tenth and final studio album to have been recorded and released during his lifetime.<ref name=\"mtvinfoii\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1614758/20090625/jackson_michael.jhtml |title=Michael Jackson's Musical Legacy, From The Jackson 5 To Invincible |author=Jayson Rodriguez |work=MTV |publisher=Viacom |date=2009-06-25 |accessdate=2010-02-13}}</ref> It was reported that it cost thirty million dollars to make the album,<ref name=\"promotioninfo\" /> making it the most expensive album ever made.<ref name=\"Branigan 20m\" />\n\n==Music and lyrics==\n\n''Invincible'' is an [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]],<ref name=NME>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/reviews/album/reviews-nme-5744|title=Michael Jackson : 'Invincible'|website=[[NME]]|date=September 12, 2005|access-date=September 16, 2018|quote=On first listen, \u2018Invincible\u2019 is a good R&B record, but certainly not pioneering}}</ref> [[Pop music|pop]]<ref name=\"ALG Invincible\"/> and [[Soul music|soul]]<ref name=\"Blender2\"/> record. The album's full length lasts over 77 minutes and contains 16 songs \u2013 fifteen of which were written (or co-written) by Jackson. It was noted that the album shifts between aggressive songs and ballads.<ref name=\"e.w.review\"/> ''Invincible'' opens with \"Unbreakable\"; the last line in the first verse recites the lyrics, \"With all that I've been through/I'm still around\".<ref name=\"RS Invincible\"/> In a 2002 interview with the magazine ''[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]'', Jackson commented on his inspiration for writing \"Speechless\", saying\n\n{{quote|You'll be surprised. I was with these kids in Germany, and we had a big water-balloon fight - I'm serious - and I was so happy after the fight that I ran upstairs in their house and wrote \"Speechless\". Fun inspires me. I hate to say that because it's such a romantic song. But it was the fight that did it. I was happy, and I wrote it in {{sic|it's}} entirety right there. I felt it would be good enough for the album. Out of the bliss comes magic, wonderment, and creativity.<ref name=vibeii>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_0yUEAAAAMBAJ |page=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_0yUEAAAAMBAJ/page/n117 108] |quote=Speechless. |title=Interview with Michael Jackson |work=[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]] |accessdate=2010-04-26|last1=Group|first1=Vibe Media|date=March 2002}}</ref>}}\n\n\"Privacy\", a reflection on Jackson's own personal experiences, is about media invasions and tabloid inaccuracies.<ref name=\"RS Invincible\"/> \"The Lost Children\" is about imperiled children.<ref name=\"RS Invincible\"/> Jackson sings in a [[Narration#Third-person|third person]] in \"Whatever Happens\". The song's lyrics, described by ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine as having a \"jagged intensity\", narrate the story of two people involved in an unnamed threatening situation.<ref name=\"RS Invincible\"/> ''Invincible'' features four ballads: \"You Are My Life\", \"Butterflies\", \"Don't Walk Away\" and \"Cry\".<ref name=\"RS Invincible\"/> \"Cry\", similar to Jackson's \"[[Man in the Mirror]]\", is about healing the world together.<ref name=\"ALG Invincible\"/> The lyrics to \"Butterflies\" and \"Break of Dawn\" were viewed as \"glaringly banal\" and it was implied that they could have been written by anyone.<ref name=\"e.w.review\"/>  \"Threatened\" was viewed as being a storyteller.<ref name=\"RS Invincible\"/> The song was viewed as a \"Thriller redux\".<ref name=\"e.w.review\"/> The song \"You Are My Life\" is about Jackson's two children at the time, Prince and Paris.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1568021/michael-jacksons-fatherhood-new-details-emerge-in-courtrooms|title= Michael Jackson's Fatherhood: New Details Emerge in Courtrooms|first=Anthony|last=McCartney|publisher=Billboard|date=June 22, 2013}}</ref> The song features Jackson singing, \"You are the sun, you make me shine, more like the stars.\"<ref name=\"e.w.review\"/>\n\n==Commercial performance==\n''Invincible'' was Jackson's first studio album since ''HIStory'' six years earlier.<ref name=\"billboardchartinvincible\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/77816/jacksons-invincible-to-debut-at-no-1|title=Jackson's 'Invincible' To Debut At No. 1|date=2001-11-07|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc|accessdate=2010-01-18}}</ref> It debuted at number one on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], with first-week sales of 363,000 units.<ref name=\"billboardchartinvincible\" /><ref name=\"billboardweek1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2001-11-17/billboard-200|title=Week of November 17, 2001|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc|accessdate=2010-01-18}}</ref> It was Jackson's fifth ''Billboard'' 200 number-one,<ref name=\"billboardchartinvincible\"/> and his fourth solo album to chart at number one in its first week; however, it sold less than ''HIStory'' in its opening week, which sold 391,000 units.<ref name=\"billboardchartinvincible\"/> ''Invincible'' also charted at number one on the [[Billboard charts|''Billboard'' R&B/Hip Hop Albums Chart]] for four weeks.<ref name=\"billboard2weeks\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2001-12-08/r-b-hip-hop-albums|title=Week of December 08, 2001|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc|accessdate=2010-02-12}}</ref> After eight weeks of release, in December 2001, ''Invincible'' was certified gold by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA) for the sales of five hundred thousand units.<ref name=\"riaacertificate\">{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH_RESULTS|title=Gold & Platinum|publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of America]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070626051113/http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH_RESULTS|archivedate=2007-06-26|accessdate=2010-02-12}}</ref> In the same month, the album was certified platinum for the sale of one million units.<ref name=\"riaacertificate\"/> On January 25, 2002, it was certified two times platinum for the sales of two million units.<ref name=\"riaacertificate\" /> In December 2004, ''Invincible'' re-entered the ''Billboard'' charts, placing at 154.<ref name=\"billboardcharts2004\">{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=michael jackson|chart=all}}|title=Invincible - Michael Jackson (2001)|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc|accessdate=2010-02-12}}</ref> It reached at number forty eight on ''Billboard''s R&B/Hip Hop Albums Chart that same week.<ref name=\"billboardcharts2004\" /> Shortly after the release of the album, in a poll conducted by ''Billboard'' magazine, \"an overwhelming majority\" of people\u201479% of 5,195 voters\u2014were not surprised by ''Invincible'' entering the ''Billboard'' 200 at number one.<ref name=\"Album poll\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/77752/poll-jacksons-chart-success-no-surprise|title=Poll: Jackson's Chart Success No Surprise|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard.]]|publisher=[[Nielsen Business Media, Inc]]|accessdate=2010-02-13}}</ref> ''Billboard'' also reported that 44% agreed with the statement, proclaiming that Jackson was \"still the King of Pop\". Another 35% said they were not surprised by the album's ranking, but doubted ''Invincible'' would hold on for a second week at the top of the chart.<ref name=\"Album poll\" /> Only 12% of people who responded to the poll said they were surprised by the album's charting debut because of Jackson's career over past six years and another 9% were taken aback by the album's success, in light of the negativity that preceded the album's release.<ref name=\"Album poll\" />\n\n''Invincible'' peaked at number one in twelve countries worldwide,<ref name=\"billboardchartinvincible\"/> including the United Kingdom, Australia, Belgium, Denmark, the Netherlands, Germany, Norway, Sweden and Switzerland.<ref name=\"billboardchartinvincible\"/><ref name=\"lescharts\"/> It also charted within the top ten in several countries, including Austria, Canada, Finland, Italy, New Zealand, and Norway.<ref name=\"lescharts\"/> ''Invincible'' was the 11th-bestselling album of 2001, shipping 5.4 million copies worldwide in that year.<ref>{{cite journal|last=White|first=Adam|date=February 16, 2002|title=Dido, Linkin Park Lead the Global 20 of 2001|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FBAEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA42|journal=Billboard|volume=114|issue=7|page=42|issn=0006-2510|accessdate=February 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nFollowing [[Death of Michael Jackson|Jackson's death]] in June 2009, his music experienced a surge in popularity.<ref name=\"sales2009july\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/268217/michael-jackson-music-sales-surge-could-last-for-months|title=Michael Jackson Music Sales Surge Could Last For Months|author=Ed Christman, Antony Bruno|date=2009-07-02|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc|accessdate=2010-02-12}}</ref> ''Invincible'' charted at number twelve on the ''Billboard'' Digital Albums Chart on July 11, 2009.<ref name=\"billboardchart091\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/#/charts/digital-albums?chartDate=2009-07-14&order=gainer|title=Week of July 11, 2009: Biggest Jump|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc|accessdate=2010-02-12}}</ref> Having not charted on the chart prior to its peak position, the album was listed as the ninth biggest jump on that chart that week.<ref name=\"billboardchart091\" /> It also charted within the top ten, peaking at number nine, on ''Billboard''{{'}}s Catalog Albums Chart on the issue date of July 18.<ref name=\"billboardcharts2004\" /> On the week of July 19, 2009, ''Invincible'' charted at number eighteen in Italy.<ref name=\"italy09\" /> ''Invincible'' peaked at number sixty four on the European Albums Chart on the charts issue date of July 25.<ref name=\"eurocharts09\" /> The album also charted at number twenty nine in Mexico in July,<ref name=\"mexico2009\" /> and eighty four on the Swiss Albums Chart on July 19, 2009.<ref name=\"swiss2009\" /> In December 2009 readers of ''Billboard'' voted ''Invincible'' the best album of the decade.<ref name=\"Album of the decade\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/#/slideshow/196807?decorator=slideshow&amp;confirm=true|title=Readers' Poll: Albums of the Decade|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111230013450/http://www.billboard.com/#/|archive-date=2011-12-30|accessdate=2010-02-12}}</ref>\n\n''Invincible'' was certified platinum by the [[British Phonographic Industry]], for the sales of over 300,000 units in the United Kingdom.<ref name=\"ukcharts1\" /> The album was certified platinum by the [[International Federation of the Phonographic Industry]] (IFPI) for the sales of 40,000 units in Switzerland. The IFPI also certified the album gold in Austria for the sales of 15,000 units. [[Australian Recording Industry Association]] certified ''Invincible'' two times platinum for the sales of 140,000 units in Australia. Other certifications include, a gold certification from [[Argentine Chamber of Phonograms and Videograms Producers]] for the sales of 20,000 units in Argentina. The album has sold around 6 million copies units worldwide.<ref name=\"Invincible 6 million copies\">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/2003/11/21/cz_1121jackson.html#6979271af267|title=Michael Jackson's Ups And Downs|author=|date=November 21, 2003|work=[[Forbes]]|publisher=|accessdate=December 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Singles==\n{{see also|Michael Jackson: 30th Anniversary Special}}{{see also|Michael Jackson singles discography}}\n{{Listen\n|help        = yes\n|filename    = Michael Jackson - You Rock My World.ogg\n|title       = \u201cYou Rock My World\u201d\n|description = Lead single from \u201cInvincible\u201d\n}}\n\nThe album spawned three official singles (\"[[You Rock My World]]\", \"[[Cry (Michael Jackson song)|Cry]]\" and \"[[Butterflies (Michael Jackson song)|Butterflies]]\") and a promotional single (\"[[Speechless (Michael Jackson song)|Speechless]]\"), although all were given limited releases.  \"You Rock My World\" was only released to radio airplay in the United States, consequently only peaking at number ten on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. Internationally, where it was released as a commercial single, it was more successful, peaking at number one in France, number two in Norway, Finland, Denmark, Belgium and the United Kingdom, number three in Italy, number four in Australia, and five in Sweden and Switzerland.<ref name=\"Y.R.M.W.Charts\">{{cite web |url=http://www.lescharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Michael+Jackson&titel=You+Rock+My+World&cat=s |title=Michael Jackson - You Rock My World (chanson) |work=LescCharts.com |publisher=Hung Medien |accessdate=2010-02-13}}</ref> The second single, \"Cry\", was not released in the United States. It was only moderately successful, with the song's most successful territories being Spain, Denmark, France, and Belgium, charting at number six, sixteen, thirty and thirty-one.<ref name=\"crycharts\">{{cite web |url=http://www.lescharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Michael+Jackson&titel=Cry&cat=s |title=Michael Jackson - Cry (chanson) |work=LesCharts.com |publisher=Hung Medien |accessdate=2010-02-13}}</ref>\n\nThe album's third single, \"Butterflies\", was only released in the United States to radio airplay, consequently only peaking at number fourteen on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 and at number two for five weeks on the [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Singles Chart]].<ref name=\"billboard singles\" />  \"[[Heaven Can Wait (Michael Jackson song)|Heaven Can Wait]]\" also charted at the bottom of the R&B/Hip-Hop Charts, at number seventy two due to [[Airplay (radio)|radio airplay]] without an official release; the song did not chart internationally.<ref name=\"billboard singles\">{{cite web |url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r553140|pure_url=yes}} |title=allmusic ((( Invincible > Charts & Awards > Billboard Singles ))) |work=[[Allmusic]] |publisher=[[Rovi Corporation]] |accessdate=2010-02-13}}</ref> \"Unbreakable\" was originally supposed to be released as a single, but it was ultimately cancelled.<ref>''Invincible'' pack-on-stocker [[Epic Records]] (2001).</ref> Despite that, the song managed to chart inside the [[Romanian Top 100]] chart, peaking at number sixty two.<ref name=\"romania\">{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050215113045/http://www.rt100.ro/editie-top-100_x10022.html|url=http://www.rt100.ro/editie-top-100_x10022.html|title=Arhiva romanian top 100 \u2013 Editia 21, saptamina 27.05-2.06, 2002|publisher=Romanian Top 100|archivedate=February 15, 2005}}</ref> It was later included on ''[[The Ultimate Collection (Michael Jackson album)|The Ultimate Collection]]'' box set in 2004.\n\n== Promotion ==\nIt was reported that the album had a budget of twenty five million dollars set aside for promotion.<ref name=\"promotioninfo\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nationalpost.com/arts/michael-jackson/story.html?id=1732696|title=Key Facts about Michael Jackson's life|author=Katherine Laidlaw|date=2009-06-25|work=[[National Post]]|publisher=[[CanWest|CanWest Global Communications]]|accessdate=2010-02-13}}</ref> Despite this, however, due to the conflicts between Jackson and his record label, little was done to promote the album.<ref name=\"tara 611\">Taraborrelli, p. 611</ref> Unlike with Jackson's post-''Thriller'' adult studio albums, there was no world tour to promote the album; a tour was planned, but cancelled due to conflicts between Jackson and Sony, and the [[September 11th Attacks|September 11th attacks]] (the latter of which had also motivated many other artists to cancel their then-upcoming concerts in late 2001 and early 2002){{cn|date=November 2019}}. There was, however, a special [[Michael Jackson: 30th Anniversary Special|30th Anniversary celebration]] at Madison Square Garden in early September 2001 to mark Jackson's 30th year as a solo artist. The singer performed one song from ''Invincible'' (\"You Rock My World\") and marked his first appearance onstage alongside his brothers since [[the Jacksons]]' [[Victory Tour (The Jacksons tour)|Victory Tour]] in 1984.<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2001/sep/08/taniabranigan|title=Jackson spends \u00a320m to be Invincible|author=Tania Branigan|date=2001-09-08|work=The Guardian|accessdate=2010-02-13|publisher=Guardian Media Group|location=London}}</ref> The show also featured performances by [[Britney Spears]], [[M\u00fda]], [[Usher (entertainer)|Usher]], [[Whitney Houston]], [[Tamia]], [[Backstreet Boys]], [['N Sync]], [[98 Degrees]], and [[Slash (musician)|Slash]], among other artists.<ref>George, p. 50\u201353</ref> The show aired on [[CBS]] in November 2001 as a two-hour television special and garnered 29.8 million viewers.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/77730/jacksons-cbs-special-moonwalks-over-rivals|title=Jackson's CBS Special Moonwalks Over Rivals|date=November 15, 2001|publisher=Billboard}}</ref>\n\nThe album's promotion was met with trouble due to internal conflicts with [[Sony Music Entertainment]] and Jackson due to his part of ownership with the company and the contract to this deal with Sony that was originally signed back in 1991. The issue stemmed back during the production of ''Invincible'' when Jackson learned that the rights to the masters of his past releases, which were to revert to him in the early 2000s, wouldn't actually revert to him until much later in the decade. When Jackson went to the lawyer who worked with him in making the deal back in 1991, he learned that the same lawyer was also working for Sony, revealing a [[conflict of interest]] he was never aware of. Not wanting to sign away his ownership in Sony Music Entertainment, Jackson elected to leave the company shortly after the album's release.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/2002/06/18/michael-jackson-divorcing-sony-music.html|title=Michael Jackson Divorcing Sony Music {{!}} Fox News|last=Friedman|first=Roger|date=2002-06-18|language=en-US|access-date=2016-09-10}}</ref> After the announcement, Sony halted promotion on the album, cancelling single releases, including a 9/11 charity single that was intended to be released before ''Invincible''. \n\nFollowing Sony's decision to abruptly end all promotion for the album, Jackson made allegations in July 2002 that Mottola was a \"devil\" and a \"racist\" who did not support his African-American artists, but merely used them for his own personal gain.<ref name=\"promotioninfo\" /><ref name=\"tara 610\u2013611\">Taraborrelli, p. 610\u2013611</ref> The singer accused Sony and the [[record industry]] of racism, deliberately not promoting or actively working against promotion of his album.<ref name=\"Falling star\">{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2003/11/19/1069027185212.html|title=Falling star|author=Bernard Zuel|date=2003-11-20|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|accessdate=2010-02-13|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]}}</ref> Sony disputed claims that they had failed to promote ''Invincible'' with sufficient energy, maintaining that Jackson refused to tour in the United States.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2002/jul/08/oliverburkeman|title=Jacko gets tough: but is he a race crusader or just a falling star?|author=Oliver Burkeman|date=2002-07-08|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=2010-02-13|publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]]|location=London}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n<!--DO NOT REMOVE ALBUM RATINGS TEMPLATE. Reviews are NO LONGER placed in the infobox, see [[WP:ALBUMS#Professional reviews]]. MAXIMUM TEN REVIEWS.-->\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"ALG Invincible\"/>\n| rev2 = ''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]''\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref name=\"Blender2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.blender.com/guide/reviews/index_409.html |title=Jacko spends a fortune on an attempt at relevance |first=John |last=Aizlewood |publisher=Blender |date=January 2002 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020417015304/http://www.blender.com/guide/reviews/index_409.html |archivedate=April 17, 2002 |quote=Invincible is a long-winded (77 minutes, 16 tracks), soulless soul album of the kind Levert might have once turned in}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev3Score = C-<ref name=\"e.w.review\" />\n| rev4 = ''[[The Guardian]]''\n| rev4Score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2001/oct/26/shopping.popandrock|work=The Guardian|title=CD review: Michael Jackson, Invincible|accessdate=April 20, 2010 | location=London | date=2002-06-25 | first=Alexis | last=Petridis}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev5Score = 6/10<ref name=\"NME Invincible\" />\n| rev6 = ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]''\n| rev6Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"Qmag\"/>\n| rev7 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev7Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"RS Invincible\"/>\n| rev8 = ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]''\n| rev8Score = {{Rating|1|5}}<ref name=\"RSguide\"/>\n| rev9 = ''[[Slant Magazine]]''\n| rev9Score = {{Rating|2.5|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/michael-jackson-invincible/95|work=[[Slant Magazine]]|author=Cinquemani, Sal|accessdate=August 7, 2010|date=October 29, 2001|title=Michael Jackson: Invincible}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[The Village Voice]]''\n| rev10Score = A\u2013<ref name=\"VV\">{{cite news|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|date=January 15, 2002|url=https://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/cg/cgv102-02.php|title=Consumer Guide: Popstakes|newspaper=[[The Village Voice]]|accessdate=March 13, 2019|via=robertchristgau.com}}</ref>\n}}\n''Invincible'' received mixed reviews from professional critics. At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream critics, the album received a mixed score of 51 based on 19 reviews.<ref name=\"Metacritic\">[http://www.metacritic.com/music/artists/jacksonmichael/invincible ''Invincible'' (2001): Reviews]. [[Metacritic]]. Retrieved on 2010-08-07.</ref> [[David Browne (journalist)|David Browne]] of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'', felt that ''Invincible'' is Jackson's \"first album since ''Off the Wall'' that offers virtually no new twists\" but remarked that the album \"feels like an anthology of his less-than-greatest hits\".<ref name=\"e.w.review\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,253595,00.html |title=Invincible (2001) |author=David Browne |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |publisher=Time Warner Inc |date=2001-11-09 |accessdate=2010-02-12}}</ref> \n\nJames Hunter of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' critiqued that the album's later ballads made the record too long.<ref name=\"RS Invincible\">{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/reviews/album/7733/37792 |title=Michael Jackson: Invincible  |author=James Hunter |work=[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]] |publisher=[[Jann Wenner|Wenner Media LLC]] |date=2001-12-06 |accessdate=2010-08-21}}</ref> Hunter also commented that Jackson and Riley made \"Whatever Happens\" \"something really handsome and smart\", allowing listeners \"to concentrate on the track's momentous rhythms\" such as \"Santana's passionate interjections and Lubbock's wonderfully arranged symphonic sweeps\".<ref name=\"RS Invincible\" /> Mark Beaumont of ''[[NME]]'' called it \"a relevant and rejuvenated comeback album made overlong\",<ref name=\"NME Invincible\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nme.com/reviews/michael-jackson/5780 |title=Michael Jackson: Invincible |author=Mark Beaumont |work=[[NME]] |publisher=[[IPC Media]] |date=2001-11-30 |accessdate=2008-07-23}}</ref> while ''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]'' also found it \"long-winded\".<ref name=\"Blender\">{{cite journal|journal=[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]|location=New York|page=117|issue=4|date=December 2001|title=Invincible review|quote=A long-winded, soulless soul album of the kind Levert might have once turned in.}}</ref>\n\nReviewing for ''[[The Village Voice]]'', [[Robert Christgau]] said that Jackson's skills as a musician are often forgotten, but noted that the album seemed too long compared to other Jackson albums. While Christgau felt some material was \"offensive\", he described the album's first three tracks as being the \"Rodney Jerkins of the year\" adding that he did not \"believe the [album's] hype matters\".<ref name=\"VV\" /> Nikki Tranter of [[PopMatters]] said that it is both innovative and meaningful because exceptional songs such as \"The Lost Children\" and \"Whatever Happens\" more than make up for overly sentimental songs like \"Heaven Can Wait\" and \"You Are My Life\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.popmatters.com/music/reviews/j/jacksonmichael-invincible2.shtml|work=[[PopMatters]]|author=Tranter, Nikki|accessdate=August 7, 2010|date=November 2001|title=Michael Jackson: Invincible}}</ref> ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]'' magazine said that it is an aurally interesting, albeit inconsistent, album.<ref name=\"Qmag\">{{cite journal|journal=[[Q (magazine)|Q]]|location=London|page=132|issue=184|date=December 2001|title=Invincible Review|quote=Though fatally flawed, Invincible does boast its fair share of sonic exhilaration.}}</ref> \n\nIn a negative review for ''[[The New York Times]]'', [[Jon Pareles]] suggested that the album is somewhat impersonal and humorless, as Jackson rehashes ideas from his past songs and is \"so busy trying to dazzle listeners that he forgets to have any fun.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9407EFD71731F93BA15753C1A9679C8B63&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=2|work=The New York Times|title=Music; To Regain Glory, The New Michael Imitates the Old|author=Mazur, Kevin|date=October 28, 2001|accessdate=April 20, 2010}}</ref> In a retrospective review for ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]'', Pareles said that ''Invincible'' showed Jackson had lost his suave quality to \"grim calculation\".<ref name=\"RSguide\">Pareles, Jon. \"[https://books.google.com/books?id=lRgtYCC6OUwC&pg=PA415#v=onepage&q&f=false Review: ''Invincible'']\". ''Rolling Stone'': 415. November 1, 2004.</ref>\n\n''Invincible'' received one [[Grammy Award]] nomination at the 2002 ceremony. The album's song \"[[You Rock My World]]\" was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Best Male Pop Vocal Performance|Best Pop Vocal Performance - Male]], but lost to [[James Taylor]]'s \"Don't Let Me Be Lonely Tonight\".<ref name=\"Grammy 2002\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/2002/grammys.htm |title=Grammy Awards 2002 |work=RockOnheNet.com |publisher=Rock On The Net |accessdate=2010-02-12}}</ref> Due to the album's release in October 2001, it was not eligible for any other nomination from the 2002 Grammy Awards.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/newsday/access/109631451.html?dids=109631451:109631451&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Feb+24%2C+2002&author=Glenn+Gamboa.+STAFF+WRITER&pub=Newsday+(Combined+editions)&desc=COVER+STORY+%2F+Music+With+Merit+%2F+With+U2+leading+the+way%2C+this+year's+Grammy+nominees+may+represent+the+best+and+the+brightest&pqatl=google |title=Cover Story/Music With Merit / With U2 leading the way, this year's Grammy nominees may represent the best and the brightest |author=Glenn Gamboa |work=[[Newsday]] |date=2002-02-24 |accessdate=2010-03-21}}</ref>\n\n=== Retrospective reviews ===\nIn retrospective reviews, ''Invincible'' has gained more positive reviews and has been cited as an early development of [[dubstep]].<ref name=\"Nanke\" /><ref name=\"OToole\" /> Jonathan Harris of [[Medium (website)|''Medium'']] wrote, \"The success of both Invincible and [[You Rock My World]] proved that Jackson's iconic style and musical formula was still viable and marketable in the 21st century and to yet another generation.\" Harris further praised the album as a \"brilliant piece of work, with each song tuned to pop perfection and at 16 tracks and more than 77 minutes, there is something on it for everyone, no matter which era or style one has enjoyed from the King of Pop. ''Invincible'' has also aged quite well. Jackson wisely did not conform to pop music standards at the time of production, leaving ''Invincible'' sounding just as fresh and distinctive as it did on the day it was released.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/@JonathanTSDM/michael-jacksons-invincible-is-all-grown-up-18-years-later-a-track-by-track-review-cdbbf7ae92de|title=Michael Jackson\u2019s \u2018Invincible\u2019 is All Grown Up: 18 Years Later, a Track by Track Review|last=Harris|first=Jonathan|date=2019-09-14|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2019-12-15}}</ref>\n\n[[AllMusic]] editor [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] commented that it has a \"spark\" and \"sound better than anything Jackson has done since ''[[Dangerous (Michael Jackson album)|Dangerous]]''.\"<ref name=\"ALG Invincible\" /> Erlewine noted that while the album had good material it was \"not enough to make ''Invincible'' the comeback Jackson needed - he really would have had to have an album that sounded free instead of constrained for that to work - but it does offer a reminder that he can really craft good pop.\"<ref name=\"ALG Invincible\" /> Writing for [http://popdose.com/ ''PopDose''], Mike Heyliger wrote \"''Invincible'' isn't the piece of shit most claim it to be. A leaner structure to the album and more sympathetic production would have resulted in a classic. But when measured against the radio junk that passes for pop-R&B these days, ''Invincible'' is stronger than ever.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://popdose.com/michael-jackson-invincible/|title=Michael Jackson: Invincible|date=2009-06-28|website=Popdose|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> \n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n| total_length = 77:01\n\n| title1          = Unbreakable\n| note1           = featuring [[The Notorious B.I.G.]]\n| writer1         = {{flat list|\n*[[Michael Jackson]]\n*[[Rodney Jerkins]]\n*[[Fred Jerkins III]]\n*[[LaShawn Daniels]]\n*Nora Payne\n*Robert Smith\n*Christopher George Latore Wallace\n}}\n| extra1          = {{flat list|\n*Jackson\n*Jerkins\n}}\n| length1         = 6:25\n\n| title2          = Heartbreaker\n| note2           = featuring Fats\n| writer2         = {{flat list|\n*Jackson\n*Jerkins\n*Jerkins III\n*Daniels\n*Mischke\n*Norman Gregg\n}}\n| extra2          = {{flat list|\n*Jackson\n*Jerkins\n}}\n| length2         = 5:10\n\n| title3          = Invincible\n| note3           = featuring Fats\n| writer3         = {{flat list|\n*Jackson\n*Jerkins\n*Jerkins III\n*Daniels\n*Gregg\n}}\n| extra3          = {{flat list|\n*Jackson\n*Jerkins\n}}\n| length3         = 4:45\n\n| title4   